### Basic usage​

​
In most cases, simply setting the preset key to the desired preset name in your Jest config should be enough to start using TypeScript with Jest (assuming you added ts-jest to your devDependencies of course):

```
preset
```

```
ts-jest
```

```
devDependencies
```

- JavaScript
- TypeScript
- JSON

```
// jest.config.js/** @type {import('ts-jest').JestConfigWithTsJest} */module.exports = { // [...] // Replace `ts-jest` with the preset you want to use // from the above list preset: 'ts-jest',}
```

```
// jest.config.js/** @type {import('ts-jest').JestConfigWithTsJest} */module.exports = { // [...] // Replace `ts-jest` with the preset you want to use // from the above list preset: 'ts-jest',}
```

```
// jest.config.tsimport type { JestConfigWithTsJest } from 'ts-jest'const jestConfig: JestConfigWithTsJest = { // [...] // Replace `ts-jest` with the preset you want to use // from the above list preset: 'ts-jest',}export default jestConfig
```

```
// jest.config.tsimport type { JestConfigWithTsJest } from 'ts-jest'const jestConfig: JestConfigWithTsJest = { // [...] // Replace `ts-jest` with the preset you want to use // from the above list preset: 'ts-jest',}export default jestConfig
```

```
// package.json{ // [...] "jest": { // Replace `ts-jest` with the preset you want to use // from the above list "preset": "ts-jest" }}
```

```
// package.json{ // [...] "jest": { // Replace `ts-jest` with the preset you want to use // from the above list "preset": "ts-jest" }}
```

Note: presets use testMatch, like Jest does in its defaults. If you want to use testRegex instead in your configuration, you MUST set testMatch to null or Jest will bail.

```
testMatch
```

```
testRegex
```

```
testMatch
```

```
null
```
